<br>
For those of you who weren't history majors it boils down to this: for most europeans when you are attacked you retreat from the attacker to prevent an escalation of violence.  This isn't cowardice, it's just a view that it's best to avoid a situation where someone might get hurt.  For most americans the view is the opposite: if confronted by an attacker, make him back down.  If your life is threatened you have the right to respond with force &amp; if you feel there are no other options you can respond with lethal force.  To use lethal force in most european courts you will have to show that you had exhausted every other option...for example you ran away until you were against a wall and could run no further.  In an american court you would prove that you truly felt like your life was in danger.<br>
<br>
BIG difference &amp; one that is obviously related to our disagreement.  Book is highly recommended if you want to understand the evolution of american attitude towards violence.<br>
<br>
